Attainment in English and Maths GCSE at grade 5 or above for children aged 14 to 16 (key stage 4)

Department:
Department for Education
Published:
10 October 2018
Last updated:
10 October 2018, see all updates
Source:
Key stage 4 statistics
Area covered:
England
Time period:
2016/17

The main facts and figures show that:

  • in 2016/17, there were 527,859 pupils at the end of key stage 4 in state-funded schools, and ethnicity was known for 521,048 (99%) of them

  • of these, 77% were White, 10% were Asian, 5% were Black, 5% were Mixed, 1.6% were in the Other ethnic group, and 0.4% were in the Chinese ethnic group

  • pupils from the Chinese ethnic group were the most likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE, while Gypsy/Roma pupils were the least likely to

  • across all ethnic groups, girls were more likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE than boys – overall, 45.7% of girls did so, compared with 39.6% of boys

  • across all ethnic groups, pupils eligible for free school meals (FSM) were less likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE than those not eligible – overall, 21.7% of FSM-eligible pupils did so, compared with 45.8% of those not eligible

  • White Irish girls eligible for FSM were the least likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in England and Maths GCSE, with 14% doing so

Things you need to know

In 2017, pupils sat reformed GCSEs in English language, English literature and maths for the first time, graded on a 9 to 1 scale (where 9 is the highest grade and 1 is the lowest). The new headline attainment measure requires pupils to achieve a grade 5 or above in either English language or literature (with no requirement to take both) and to achieve a grade 5 or above in EBacc maths.

Please be aware that some of the statistics quoted here for some ethnic groups are based on very small numbers of pupils (for example, only 131 Chinese children were eligible for free school meals in 2016/17) and are highly variable over time.

Attainment is lower for children from a Traveller of Irish heritage background – however, there were only 118 pupils from this background at the end of key stage 4 in 2016/17. This was a much smaller number than for other ethnic groups (for example, there were 21,323 Pakistani pupils at the end of key stage 4). Therefore, data comparisons between Traveller of Irish Heritage pupils and other ethnic groups may be unreliable.

The ethnicity of 1.3% of pupils (6,811) is not known. This includes pupils whose ethnicity was not surveyed, pupils who refused to be surveyed, and pupils whose ethnicity could not be determined.

The Department of Education (DfE) has excluded, or ‘suppressed’, very small numbers (for example, values of 1 or 2, a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved, or 0, 1 or 2 pupils who did not achieve a particular level).

This is because, where the size of the ethnic group population is small enough that an individual’s identity could be revealed, information is suppressed to preserve confidentiality. This is consistent with DfE’s statistical policy statement on confidentiality.

Data for some Muslim, Sikh and Hindu schools was not included in the statistics for faith schools, because the small numbers of pupils make it impossible to draw meaningful conclusions about their attainment. Data for faith schools is also only provided for pupils in state-funded mainstream schools.

Schools can ask for a pupil to be removed from their performance results if the pupil:

  • arrived recently from overseas and their first language isn’t English
  • was admitted following a permanent exclusion from another school
  • is not at the end of key stage 4
  • has left England to live abroad
  • has died

Pupils removed from a school’s performance results may still be included in the national figures.

What the data measures

This data measures the percentage of pupils within each ethnic group achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE.

It also looks at the total number of children achieving a grade 5 or above, and analyses each ethnic group’s percentage share of that total.

The data covers the academic year 2016/17 (September 2016 to July 2017).

Key stage 4 covers school years 10 and 11, when children are aged 14 to 16.

The ethnic categories used in this data

This data uses categories from the Department for Education’s school census, which is broadly based on the 2001 national Census, with 3 exceptions:

  • Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma children have been separated into 2 categories
  • Sri Lankan has been added to the Asian but is not reported separately
  • Chinese pupils have been assigned a separate category

These changes were made after consultations with local authorities and lobby groups.

The categories in the school census are as follows:

White:

  • White British
  • White Irish
  • Traveller of Irish Heritage
  • Gypsy/Roma
  • Other White

Mixed:

  • White and Black Caribbean
  • White and Black African
  • White and Asian
  • Other Mixed background

Asian:

  • Indian
  • Pakistani
  • Bangladeshi
  • Sri Lankan
  • Other Asian background

Black:

  • Black African
  • Black Caribbean
  • Other Black background

Chinese Other

Information is provided for both detailed and broad ethnic groups where possible and when the data is available.

The 6 broad categories used are as follows:

  • Asian
  • Black
  • Chinese
  • Mixed
  • White
  • Other ethnic group

However, data by local authority, basis for school admission, school type, special educational needs, and religion of school is only provided for 5 broad ethnic groups. Information about the specific ethnic categories is excluded to preserve confidentiality and ensure individuals cannot be identified. Information about the Other ethnic group is not given because DfE does not publish data for this group at the local authority level.

The 5 broad categories are as follows:

  • Asian
  • Black
  • Chinese
  • Mixed
  • White

Summary

The data shows that:

  • in 2016/17, 42.6% of all pupils achieved grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE, making this the national average
  • pupils from the Chinese ethnic group were the most likely to achieve grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (with 72% doing so), followed by pupils from the Indian group (61.9%)
  • the Gypsy/Roma ethnic group had the lowest percentage of pupils achieving grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (4.7% did so), followed by children from a Traveller of Irish Heritage background (9.3% did so)

Summary

Eligibility for free school meals (FSM) is used as an indicator of deprivation by the Department for Education. See the Methodology section for more information about who qualifies for FSM.

The data shows that:

  • 13.3% of pupils (69,261 children) at the end of key stage 4 were eligible for free school meals (FSM) in 2016/17
  • 23.8% of pupils from the Other ethnic group were eligible for FSM, followed by 21.8% of Black pupils, 18.3% of pupils of Mixed ethnicity, 16.7% of Asian pupils, 11.6% of White pupils and 6.3% of pupils from the Chinese ethnic group
  • across all ethnic groups, FSM-eligible pupils were less likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE than those not eligible – overall, 21.7% of pupils eligible for FSM achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE, while 45.8% of all other pupils did so
  • of the broad ethnic groups, pupils from the Chinese ethnic group had the highest percentage of FSM-eligible pupils achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (67.9% did so)
  • White FSM-eligible pupils were least likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (17.4% did so)
  • Irish pupils had the largest gap in attainment between those eligible for FSM and those not eligible, with 18.6% of FSM-eligible pupils achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE, compared with 59.8% of those not eligible (a 41.2 percentage point gap)

Summary

The data shows that:

  • Isles of Scilly in the South West had the highest percentage of pupils achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (68.4%), but this area only includes 19 pupils so this result should be treated with caution; Trafford in the North West had the next highest percentage of pupils achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (62.7%)
  • Knowsley in the North West had the lowest percentage of pupils achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (at 24.6%)
  • 86.8% of Asian pupils achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE in Sutton (London), compared with 28.0% in Stoke-on-Trent (West Midlands), making these the local authorities where Asian pupils were most and least likely to achieve a grade 5 or above
  • 70.3% of Black pupils achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE in Southend-on-Sea (East of England), compared with 22.1% in Gloucestershire (South West)
  • 100% of Chinese pupils achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE in 8 local authorities, compared with 33.3% in Windsor and Maidenhead (South East)
  • 65.5% of pupils with Mixed ethnicity achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE in North Lincolnshire (Yorkshire and the Humber), compared with 19.5% in Rochdale (North West)
  • 63.5% of White pupils achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE in Hammersmith and Fulham (London), compared with 24.5% in Knowsley (North West)

Summary

The data shows that:

  • across all ethnic groups, boys were less likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE compared with girls: overall, 45.7% of girls achieved a grade 5 or above compared with 39.6% of boys
  • of the broad ethnic groups, Chinese girls had the highest percentage achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (76.5%), while Black boys had the lowest (34.1%)
  • the largest gap between boys and girls was in the Other Black ethnic group, where 37.2% of girls achieved a a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE compared with 27.1% of boys (a gap of 10.1 percentage points)

Summary

Eligibility for free school meals (FSM) is used as an indicator of deprivation by the Department for Education. See the Methodology section for more information about who qualifies for FSM.

The data shows that:

  • overall, in every ethnic group, boys and girls not eligible for FSM did better than those who were eligible
  • across all ethnic groups, FSM-eligible girls were more likely to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE than FSM-eligible boys, except for White Irish pupils
  • Chinese boys and girls eligible for FSM had the highest percentage achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE, at 62.3% and 74.2% respectively
  • White Irish girls eligible for FSM had the lowest percentage of pupils achieving a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE (14%)
  • the largest gap between FSM-eligible girls and boys, at 11.9 percentage points, was found among Chinese pupils

Summary

The data shows that:

  • in most local authorities, a higher percentage of girls achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE than boys
  • among Asian pupils, the biggest gap between girls and boys was in Cornwall – 62.5% of boys achieved a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE, compared with 23.1% of girls (a gap of 39.4 percentage points)
  • among Black pupils, the biggest gap between girls and boys was in Dudley in the West Midlands – 44.7% of girls achieved a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE, compared with 25.6% of boys (a gap of 19.1 percentage points)
  • among pupils from the Chinese ethnic group, the biggest gap was Norfolk in the East – 77.8% of girls achieved a grade 5 or above, compared with 50.0% of boys (a gap of 27.8 percentage points)
  • among pupils with Mixed ethnicity, the biggest gap between girls and boys was in Northumberland in the North East – 40.0% of girls achieved a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE, compared with 73.3% of boys (a gap of 33.3 percentage points)
  • among White pupils, the biggest gap between girls and boys was in Westminster in London – 68.4% of girls achieved a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE, compared with 44.0% of boys (a gap of 24.4 percentage points)
  • please be aware that the statistics quoted here for attainment in English and Maths by ethnic group, gender and local authority may be based on small numbers of pupils and can therefore be highly variable over time

Summary

This data groups schools into the following 3 categories, according to whether they select their pupils by ability:

  • selective schools
  • non-selective schools in highly selective areas (where 25% or more of state-funded secondary places are in state-funded selective schools)
  • all other non-selective schools (including schools in local authorities with some selection, as well as those with no selection)

In 2016/17, 22,715 of pupils (4%) at the end of key stage 4 were in selective schools, 33,611 (6%) in non-selective schools in highly selective areas, and 460,255 (89%) in non-selective schools in other areas.

The data shows that:

  • across all ethnic groups and in all types of school, a higher percentage of girls than boys achieved a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE
  • Chinese girls in selective schools did best: 98.3% achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE
  • White boys in non-selective schools in highly selective areas did least well: 27.1% achieved a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE

Summary

Pupils with special education needs (SEN) have learning difficulties or disabilities that make it harder for them to learn than most children of the same age.

From 2015, pupils have been categorised as follows:

  • no identified SEN
  • SEN support: extra or different help is given from that provided as part of the school's usual curriculum, and the class teacher and SEN coordinator (SENCO) may receive advice or support from outside specialists
  • SEN statement or education, health and care (EHC) plan: a pupil is given a SEN statement or an EHC plan once a formal assessment has been made

In 2016/17, there were 74,420 pupils at the end of key stage 4 with special education needs: 79% were White, 8% were Asian, 6% were Black, 5% were Mixed and 0.2% were Chinese.

Of the 74,420 SEN pupils in total, 74% had SEN support and 26% had SEN with a statement or EHC plan.

The data shows that:

  • across all ethnic groups, pupils with special education needs (SEN) were less likely to achieve an a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE than non-SEN pupils – 12.8% of SEN pupils did so, compared with 47.6% of pupils without SEN
  • of all pupils with special education needs, Chinese pupils were the most likely to achieve a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE (24.2%), and Black pupils the least likely (11.2%)
  • looking at those with SEN support, Chinese pupils were the most likely to achieve a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE (29.7%) and Black pupils the least likely (13.3%)
  • of SEN pupils with a statement or EHC plan, Chinese pupils were the most likely to achieve a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE (10.8%) and Mixed pupils the least likely (4.0%)

  • Muslim schools
  • Sikh schools
  • Hindu schools

In 2016/17, there were 517,756 pupils at the end of key stage 4 in state-funded mainstream schools in England.

82% of these pupils attended schools with no religious character, 6% attended Church of England schools, 10% attended Roman Catholic schools, 2% attended Other Christian faith schools, 0.3% attended Jewish, 0.1% attended Muslim, 0.1% attended Sikh and 0.02% attended Hindu schools.

The data shows that:

  • overall, pupils at Jewish schools were most like to achieve a grade 5 or above in English and Maths GCSE, with 66.0% doing so
  • boys with Mixed ethnicity at Muslim schools, and pupils from the Chinese ethnic group at Jewish schools, were most likely to achieve a grade 5 and above in English and Maths GCSE – 100.0% did so

Methodology

Methodology

The key stage 4 datasets are compiled using information matched together from 3 data sources:

  • prior attainment records (key stage 2 results)

  • school census records

  • qualification entries and results collected from awarding bodies

The census data is provided for all pupils aged 5 and over on 31 August 2016. Any information that still needs to be collected is recorded as ‘not yet obtained’.

If a pupil or parent refused to give information, this is recorded as 'refused'.

These statistics include pupils whose ethnicity was not obtained, who refused to respond, or whose ethnicity could not be determined.

Key stage 4 data received from awarding bodies are combined with pupil characteristics from the school census and prior attainment. Records are matched, using identifiers such as surname, forename, date of birth, unique pupil number, gender and postcode. This successfully matches around 98% of results.

The statistics in this commission cover the data collated for the 2017 secondary school performance tables. The performance tables and the related statistical first release report results based on pupils at the end of key stage 4, who are typically aged 15 at the start of the academic year.

The coverage of the local authority and regional statistics is state-funded schools in England. This includes city technology colleges and academies but excludes hospital schools, pupil referral units and alternative provision.

Pupils are included in the figures for free school meals (FSM) if their families have claimed eligibility for FSM at the time of the annual spring school census. This FSM definition includes all who were eligible to receive free school meals, not only those who actually received free school meals. Pupils not eligible for free school meals or unclassified pupils are described as ‘Non-FSM’ or ‘All other pupils’.

Parents are able to claim FSM if they receive a qualifying benefit.

FSM is used as an indicator of disadvantage, but when drawing conclusions, it should be remembered that not all eligible parents apply for FSM and families who don’t quite reach the eligibility threshold for FSM may still be suffering deprivation.

Suppression rules and disclosure control

Values of 1 or 2, or a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved; or 0, 1 or 2 pupils who did not achieve a particular level are suppressed in circumstances where non-suppression would lead to disclosure of pupils. Some additional figures have been suppressed to prevent the possibility of a suppressed figure being revealed.

This suppression is consistent with DfE’s statistical policy statement on confidentiality (PDF).

The Code of Practice for Official Statistics requires DfE to take reasonable steps to ensure that their published or disseminated statistics protect confidentiality.

For more information about DfE’s disclosure control procedures for its statistical releases please see DfE’s statistical policy statement on confidentiality (PDF).

Rounding

Figures in charts and tables are rounded to the nearest whole number.

In downloads, percentages are given to 1 decimal place.
